To hack or not to

I should admit that the title is a slightly mischievous and used as a trap, please accept my apologies for any disappointment. Wireshark can be used equally wearing either the black or white hat, meaning: Reading the tutorial one can indeed learn how to do what the title promises, however Wireshark can do much more and be a powerful tool for web masters, network administrators and home users. Despite, now days is almost impossible to actually read HTTPS/SSL Wiresharks communications output due to widespread encryption (more discussion about this at the end).

What is Wireshark


Wireshark is a network packet analyser which can be used to try and capture network packets that going through the network port of the device that the application runs on and then display that packet data as detailed as possible.

Background

The program was initially called Ethereal and its development started in 1998. Since then is licenced as open source software, which also means it is free of charge to use, and there have been numerous contributors to new versions that are currently produces in a monthly turnover. For more details about the history and the softwares background see the user guide.

Applications

Some examples of how the program can be used:

        Troubleshoot network problems

        Examine security problems

        Identify security vulnerabilities

        Verify network applications

        Learn network protocol internals

Limitations

Note that Wiresharks capabilities are limited. For heavy traffic networks webmasters and network admins consider dedicated solutions such those in this extensive article on LAN analysers.

Features

        Monitor network traffic and display packets as they transferred

        Export/import files with captured data

        Large variety of protocols support. For a complete list see link

        Also variety of supported media. Complete list under here

1.   Download

Visit the Wireshark download page and chose the corresponding version for your system.

        Note that the page will attempt to automatically highlight the appropriate download for the device we are at, it may be a good idea then to do the download using the device that we plan to use Wireshark on (ie: the server)

        Security notice: Official Windows and macOS installers are signed by the Wireshark Foundation and are considered safe

2.   Install

For devices with windows and mac operating systems the installations should be straightforward. Linux and FreeBSD however require installation from source. In any case, the user guide has all the relevant information and dont forget to check the Getting Help section at the end of this tutorial.

command-line version

The distribution comes with a TShark, the programs command-line version. However, we are only focusing on Windows in the tutorial.

 

Installing WinPcap

WinPcap is mandatory for capturing live network traffic and that is why it is automatically installed by Wireshark installer by default, except if we chose otherwise during the installation (figure2), which you should not really do if you wish to follow this tutorial.


Despite, if for any reason WinPcap is not installed after Wiresharks installation, we can do so after running Winshark for first time by using the WinPcap entry in the Programs and Features control panel.

Run WinPcap at boot?

Yes, during WinPcap installation (following Wiresharks installation) must leave the Automatically start the WinPcap driver at boot time option checked.

This however has a drawback. When the WinPcap driver (called NPFOnce) is loaded, every local user can capture from it until it's stopped again. Simply stopping Wireshark won't stop the WinPcap driver! It might not be ideal that any local user can also capture from the network while the driver is loaded, but this cannot be currently circumvented. More information about WinPcap here.

3.   Setup a capture

First of all, start Wireshark up, if you havent done so.

Are you allowed to do this?

Before moving on make sure you can confirm that:

You allowed to capture packets from the network you are working on. Corporate policies or applicable law might prevent you from doing it on this network.

If you must change network cabling to start a capture, ensure that you are allowed to do so! Network administrators and other people are usually not amused with re-arrangements to "their" network

Choose interface

Select menu: Capture Options and the Capture Interfaces dialog box pops up.

This dialog box will only show the local interfaces Wireshark can access and will also hide interfaces marked as hidden in Interface Options (third tab in the dialog box).

We just need to select the connection that we wish to monitor and the most common option for home-computers is the eth0 or Wi-Fi.

4.   Capture


Just click the [Start] button in lower right corner in Capture Interfaces dialog box.

Start/stop

Note that we can always start and stop the service either from menu: Capture Start or from the two left-most buttons on the main toolbar.


The capture window

Displays all the packets and their details. The screen is split vertically in three parts:

1.     packet list pane

2.     tree view

3.     byte view

Packet list pane

Once the process starts we can see lines filling up the upper part of the screen, this is the packet list pane, and these lines are the actual packets as they are captured.

Tree view pane

When clicking on a packet in the list we can see its details in the tree view.

Byte view panes

These are the contents of the selected packets in a binary format.


Data everywhere

Clearly, the amount of info at this stage is large for a beginner and not easy to understand. The more one knows about networks and protocols the clearer the image is, else there is always Google. As you may guess we cannot go at such level of detail in this tutorial as it is out of scope, however, the next tip (filters) can be very useful.

Packet view


To focus on a particular packet just double click on it (in packet list pane). This will pop up the Packet view screen (figure 8) where are all the packets details (same as in tree and byte panes).

Filters

While at main screen, we may wish to consider filtering the packet capture to reduce clutter. To set a filter:

        Choose, Menu: Capture > Options > Capture Filter. The Wireshark Capture Filter window will appear where we can set various filters.

        Alternatively, to select packets based on protocol type (ie: to see only HTTP communications), we simply type the protocol in which we are interested in the Filter: field in the filter toolbar (figure 9) and press enter to initiate the filter.

Filter criteria

We can filter on any protocol that Wireshark understands. We can also filter on any field that a dissector adds to the tree view.

For example, to narrow the packet list pane down to only those packets to or from the IP address 192.168.0.1, use ip.addr==192.168.0.1.

Remove any filter


By activating a filter, the main packets screen will only show the relevant packets. If you wish to go back to normal view, just click on the X button at the right-hand side of the filter toolbar.

Filters in Wireshark is a large chapter involving programming and more. For information on filters have a look at Wiresharks official wiki page on the subject and their filters reference list.

Follow the stream

Lets say that while analysing the packet traces at main window screen, one packet draws our attention and we wish to see the whole conversation/stream (the preceding and potentially following data).


Just right click on the packet and select: follow > *stream (* we need to select the corresponding protocol depending on what type of packet it is, thankfully Wiresharks smart algorithms do the work for us, deactivating all the wrong options and leaving the right one(s) for us to click).

This sets an appropriate display filter and pop up a dialog box (figure 9) with all the data from the TCP stream laid out in order.

Did you notice the word filter? As discussed earlier in filters this will change the main screens view to display only the packets from this stream. And even closing the pop-up stream window the filter will remain active. The only way out is to close the filter as we saw earlier in filters (click the X button at the right-hand side of the filter toolbar).

How to use the information in the tutorial.

We discussed cool great features in Wireshark but what can we do with these? In case you need some ideas:

Troubleshoot slow internet. There are cases that some applications or users are flooding the network (sources demanding applications or heavy downloads) with what we saw in this tutorial we can see the heavy users.

As discussed in the beginning, Wireshark allows us to read text or images (as promised in title), however as most communications now days are fortunately(!) encrypted and the jargon outputted on byte view is just rubbish. It is almost impossible to unencrypt it but if you are keen have a look at this introductory video or Googles advice for webmasters on how to Secure your site with HTTPS.

Add more ideas here

What is beyond Wireshark

Wireshark is just an analyser. Gathering data and displaying them in a useful order. This network data and more is already available in the system and there are other ways to access it and. This however is beyond our scope here and if interested there are numerous sources to explore, perhaps starting with some Cisco certificate, CCNA, study guides

Final note

As you may have guessed already we havent even scratched the surface of what Wireshark can do tutorial. Obviously, there are much more into this and is powerful and fun to explore. To find out more about the program, feel free to visit the official site, wiki or even user manual. Google is always a good place to go too.

 

Thank you for reading and wish you enjoy exploring the software.
